The AF is far worse than I had imagined. Thanks, John!  And for the  
image of the feedback loop between publishers and lexicographers, and 
the impossibility of ever choosing a single &quot;correct speech&quot;


On 7/15/2017 10:53 PM, John Cowan cowan@... [Read_Alphabet] wrote:
&gt;
&gt; On Sat, Jul 15, 2017 at 1:12 PM, Vincent Reilly vin.reilly@... 
&gt; &lt;mailto:vin.reilly@...&gt; [Read_Alphabet] 
&gt; &lt;Read_Alphabet@yahoogroups.com &lt;mailto:Read_Alphabet@yahoogroups.com&gt;&gt; 
&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt;     1. Would it be desirable to create an English Academy, modeled on
&gt;     the Academie Française? Would it even be possible?
&gt;
&gt; Let&#39;s not.  The AF is a horrible model.  It takes forever to do 
&gt; anything, its dictionary is neither very good nor very authoritative 
&gt; in actual use (though it is theoretically official in France), it has 
&gt; a history of opposing all recognition of the regional languages of 
&gt; France.  Of the 35 present members (five seats are vacant), only six 
&gt; were born outside France and only one (Haitian Canadian Dany 
&gt; Laferrière) is living outside France; this despite the fact that less 
&gt; than a third of French-speakers live in France.
&gt;
&gt;     2. If the Read Alphabet were widely adopted, might we no longer
&gt;     see the value of standardization, in favor of spelling how you
&gt;     speak? Is this a bad thing or a good thing?
&gt;
&gt; Historically, standardization has been something publishers have 
&gt; insisted on.  If every author spells just as they like, the result is 
&gt; orthographic chaos, and proofreading becomes impossible.  Even 
&gt; Cherokee, which was not written until the 19C, has a fairly 
&gt; well-established standard spelling that doesn&#39;t agree exactly with any 
&gt; one of the various dialects of Cherokee, themselves products of the 
&gt; 19C as well.
&gt;
&gt; At present, orthographies are stabilized by a feedback loop between 
&gt; publishers and lexicographers.  Publishers adopt a particular 
&gt; dictionary as their authority for spelling, but the spellings that 
&gt; appear in dictionaries are those used by publishers.  The process 
&gt; rapidly converges on a standard orthography without any single source 
&gt; of authority.
&gt;
&gt;     3. One way to standardize phonetic spelling to standardize a
&gt;     proper manner of speaking. (I think this refers back to question
&gt;     1). Should one accent be considered &quot;standard&quot;?And which one? And why?
&gt;
&gt; That&#39;s hopeless.  The matter would instantly become a political 
&gt; football (round or oval) between the U.S. and the UK, with the rest of 
&gt; the world acting as something between astonished bystanders and swing 
&gt; voters.
&gt;
&gt; What can, and I believe should, be done is to establish a writing 
&gt; system that makes the distinctions required by any of the living 
&gt; accents of Standard English.  In this way, English-speakers would 
&gt; easily be able to pronounce any written word according to their own 
&gt; accent, but would have to learn in some cases how a word should be 
&gt; written so as to be read correctly by all English-speakers.  The Read 
&gt; alphabet already provides this in the matter of post-vocalic &quot;r&quot;, but 
&gt; would need a few more letters to cover all the vowel sounds of English.
&gt;
&gt; For example Read has only one letter for the sounds of &quot;term&quot;, &quot;dirt&quot;, 
&gt; and &quot;nurse&quot;, but would require three for Scottish English, which 
&gt; pronounces them all differently, and for Irish English, which 
&gt; pronounces two of them the same but the other differently.  (Note that 
&gt; traditional orthography already caters to this requirement.)  This 
&gt; would be a small burden for other writers of English, but would 
&gt; eliminate the notion that some accents are preferred to others, as 
&gt; there is no internationally preferred accent.
&gt;
&gt; 


